5000|$|In England, however, {{before any}} demand for payment {{has been made}} by the {{creditor}} on the surety, the latter can, as soon as the principal debtor has made default, compel the creditor, on giving him an indemnity against costs and expenses, to sue the principal debtor if the latter is solvent and able to pay. and a similar remedy is also open to the surety in America. [...] In neither of these countries nor in Scotland can one of several sureties, when sued for the whole guaranteed debt by the creditor, compel the latter to divide his claim among the sureties, and reduce it to the share and proportion of each surety. However, this <b>beneficium</b> <b>divisionis,</b> as it is called in Roman law, is recognized by many existing codes.|$|E

